          "body": "The chapter's opening verb is chazaq — Jehoiada 'strengthened himself.' Six years of silence are broken not by a popular uprising but by a priest who resolved to act. Before any weapon is drawn or any gate is assigned, Jehoiada makes a covenant (berit, v.1). The structural priority of covenant over strategy is the Chronicler's first theological move. Five military commanders are bound; they recruit the Levites and family heads from across Judah; the full assembly is covenanted in the house of God. The warrant for the entire action is stated in a single sentence: 'the king's son shall reign, as the LORD has spoken concerning the sons of David' (v.3). Jehoiada does not appeal to justice, to popular sentiment, or to his own authority. He appeals to a word already spoken. The Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7:12-16 is the legal ground on which this restoration stands. Every subsequent action in the chapter is the outworking of that prior divine speech."
