          "body": "Verse 11 is the chapter's centerpiece and contains its most theologically dense detail. Two objects are placed on Joash simultaneously: the nezer (the crown) and the edut (the testimony). The edut is the written Torah-document — a reference almost certainly to the Deuteronomic provision of Deuteronomy 17:18-20, which requires the king to write his own copy of the law and read it all the days of his life. Calvin noted that placing the law with the crown was the clearest possible statement that the king of Judah reigns under, not above, the word of God. Jehoiada and his sons anoint Joash — the verb mashach is the root of 'messiah' (mashiach, anointed one). The coronation is thus a messianic act in the technical sense: a Davidic king anointed with oil at the LORD's appointed time, bound by covenant to the Torah, acclaimed by the people. The acclamation 'Long live the king!' (yikhyi ha-melekh) is not merely ceremonial enthusiasm; it is the formal recognition of legitimacy."
